    "summarizer": {
      "general_reader_takeaway": "This paper proposes that an alternative cosmological model \u2014 one in which the fundamental constants of nature slowly change as the universe expands \u2014 can also explain why galaxies rotate faster at their edges than their visible matter alone would predict, without invoking invisible \"dark matter.\" The review board found the core idea speculative but not obviously wrong. However, the paper's main test is compromised: the baryonic rotation curve that the model claims to predict is largely reverse-engineered from the very observational data it is compared against, which strips the comparison of independent evidential weight. The most important unresolved gap is that the paper provides no physical law governing how the model's central parameter should vary inside a galaxy.",
      "reviewer": "claude",
      "technical_takeaway": "The paper extends the CCC+TL framework to galaxy rotation curves by showing that modified Friedmann equations contain \u03b1-matter and \u03b1-energy terms that can substitute for dark matter when \u03b1 is allowed to vary locally with baryonic density. All three reviewers across two cycles identified two core issues: (1) the local radial profile \u03b1(R) is asserted without any governing field equation, Lagrangian, or screening law \u2014 making the mechanism an adjustable ansatz rather than a prediction; and (2) the fitting procedure is substantially circular \u2014 X(R) is extracted by numerical differentiation of the observed velocity V_o, and the resulting baryonic curve V_bX is integrated back from the same data and compared against SPARC baryonic estimates, so agreement is not an independent test. A third major objection, elevated to \"fatal\" by one reviewer, is that the modified Friedmann equations assume a homogeneous, isotropic FLRW metric and cannot be applied as local gravitational source terms in a virialized disk galaxy without a derivation of the CCC post-Newtonian or thin-disk limit that is absent here. Quantitative goodness-of-fit metrics are absent; only visual agreement is reported for seven galaxies under a spherical approximation."
